Eventually all that used gear piles up as medical waste that needs to be safely discarded.
The daily output of medical waste reached 240 metric tons, about the weight of an adult blue whale.
And some things that aren’t usually considered medical waste, like food, now need to be handled more carefully after coming in contact with a COVID-19 patient.
“We are closely monitoring the situation with all relevant agencies to determine next steps.”“It’s a rapidly changing environment”The CDC says that medical waste from COVID-19 can be treated the same way as regular medical waste.
People handling health care waste should wear appropriate gearPeople handling health care waste in particular should wear appropriate gear, including boots, aprons, long-sleeved gowns, thick gloves, masks, and goggles or face shields, according to recommendations from the World Health Organization.